The paper deals with computational social choice, which involves the study of algorithms and computational complexity in social choice scenarios. The concept of approximate AND-homomorphism is related to Boolean functions, which falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). The paper also discusses judgement aggregation, which is a topic in game theory (cs.GT) and social choice theory (cs.SI). The characterization of approximate solutions to the eigenvalue equation involves the use of probability and expectation, which are concepts in probability theory and statistics (cs.LG). Finally, the paper deals with functions on binary inputs, which is related to data structures (cs.DS).
